get_period <- function(time) {
  if (is.na(time)) return(NA_character_)
  hour <- floor(time / 100)
  if (hour >= 0 & hour < 6)  return("early morning")
  if (hour >= 6 & hour < 12) return("morning")
  if (hour >= 12 & hour < 18) return("afternoon")
  if (hour >= 18 & hour <= 23) return("evening")
  return(NA_character_) 
}
flights_clean <- flights[
  !is.na(flights$dep_time) &
  !is.na(flights$arr_time) &
  floor(flights$dep_time / 100) <= 23 &
  floor(flights$arr_time / 100) <= 23,
]
flights_clean$dep_period <- sapply(flights_clean$dep_time, get_period)
flights_clean$arr_period <- sapply(flights_clean$arr_time, get_period)

flights_clean <- flights_clean[!is.na(flights_clean$dep_period) & !is.na(flights_clean$arr_period), ]

The majority of flights departed between 6 AM and 6 PM, with the morning and afternoon periods showing the highest counts. Very few flights departed during the early morning hours. The arrival distribution follows a similar trend â most flights landed in the morning and afternoon, while early morning arrivals were uncommon.This pattern indicates that commercial flight operations are strongly concentrated in daytime hours, minimizing late-night and overnight flights. After excluding all cancelled flights and any with missing or invalid times, approximately 3.2% of valid NYC flights in 2013 were âred-eyeâ flights those departing in the afternoon or evening and arriving in the early morning or morning.

#4: The missing relationship in the diagram is that each weather observation is linked to a specific airport. This relationship exists through the origin field in the weather table, which corresponds to the faa field in the airports table. To represent this in the diagram, an arrow should be drawn from weather.origin to airports.faa. This indicates that each weather record belongs to a specific airport, establishing a foreign key relationship between the two tables.

names <- c("year", "month", "day", "hour", "origin")

weather$weather_id <- ""

for (var in names) {
  weather$weather_id <- paste0(
    weather$weather_id,
    ifelse(weather$weather_id == "", "", "-"),
    weather[[var]]
  )
}

num_dupes <- sum(duplicated(weather$weather_id))

sum(duplicated(weather$weather_id))

Ans: after creating a new variable weather_id by combining year, month, day, hour, and origin, I found 3 duplicated weather_id values (2013-11-3-1 at EWR, JFK, and LGA). These duplicates exist because daylight saving time ended on November 3, 2013, causing the 1 AM hour to occur twice. Since we used only year, month, day, hour, and origin, these two distinct 1 AM observations appear as duplicates.

  summarise(mean_delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE))

airports_delay <- airports %>%
  inner_join(avg_delay_dest, by = c("faa" = "dest")) %>%
  filter(!is.na(lat), !is.na(lon))


usa <- map_data("state")

top5 <- airports_delay %>%
  top_n(5, mean_delay)

ggplot() +
  geom_polygon(
    data = usa,
    aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group),
    fill = "gray85",
    color = "white",
    linewidth = 0.3
  ) +
  geom_point(
    data = airports_delay,
    aes(x = lon, y = lat, color = mean_delay),
    size = 4.2,
    alpha = 0.9
  ) +
  geom_text(
    data = top5,
    aes(x = lon, y = lat, label = faa),
    vjust = -1,
    fontface = "bold",
    size = 4,
    color = "black"
  ) +
  scale_color_gradientn(
    colors = c("#1E88E5", "#A5D6A7", "#FFF59D", "#F57C00", "#C62828"),
    name = "Avg Delay (min)"
  ) +
  coord_fixed(1.3, xlim = c(-125, -66), ylim = c(25, 50)) +
  labs(
    title = "Average Departure Delays by Destination Airport (2013)",
    subtitle = "Major U.S. airports colored by mean departure delay",
    x = NULL,
    y = NULL
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 13) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 16, hjust = 0.5),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 12, color = "gray40", hjust = 0.5),
    axis.text = element_blank(),
    panel.grid = element_blank(),
    panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white", color = NA),
    plot.background = element_rect(fill = "white", color = NA),
    legend.position = "bottom",
    legend.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
    legend.key.width = unit(1.3, "cm")
  )

The map illustrates the spatial distribution of mean departure delays across U.S. airports in 2013. Warm colors (orange/red) indicate airports with higher average delays, while cooler colors (blue/green) show lower delays. Major airports such as ATL, ORD, and EWR exhibit the longest delays, reflecting congestion and high traffic density, while smaller regional airports show shorter average delays.

      precip > 0.3 ~ "Heavy"
    ),
    visib_cat = case_when(
      visib >= 8 ~ "Clear",
      visib >= 4 & visib < 8 ~ "Moderate",
      visib < 4 ~ "Low"
    ),

      wind_speed < 5 ~ "Calm",
      wind_speed >= 5 & wind_speed < 15 ~ "Moderate",
      wind_speed >= 15 ~ "Strong"
    ),
    temp_cat = case_when(
      temp < 32 ~ "Cold (<32Â°F)",

The violin + boxplot visualization compares flight departure delays under different weather conditions after excluding missing data. Overall, the distributions reveal that precipitation and visibility have the strongest effects on delays, while wind speed and temperature show much smaller influence.

Flights departing during heavy or moderate precipitation show noticeably higher median delays and a wider spread, indicating that rainfall and snow events substantially slow operations. Similarly, low-visibility conditions correspond to increased delay variability, suggesting reduced visibility (e.g., fog) disrupts scheduling. In contrast, wind speed and temperature display relatively consistent delay distributions across categories, implying limited direct impact on flight timing.

Taken together, these results indicate that precipitation intensity and reduced visibility are the two weather phenomena most associated with longer and more variable departure delays in 2013 New York City flights.
